                <note type="abstract">Examines the Arabic Version of the “Apology of Patriarch Timothy I”, the anonymous “On the Triune Nature of God” (MS Sinai Arabic 154), and the “Debate of Theodore Abū Qurra at the Court of al-Maʾmūn”. The author argues that Arabic testimony collections served as “theological manuals for apologists”. Accordingly, they stand in the tradition of earlier Greek and Latin testimonia but take a shape of their own since they were fashioned to answer new challenges. Not the burgeoning translations of the Bible into Arabic but the Qurʾān is the driving force behind the compilation of testimony collections.</note>
